Environment-climate: For a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The engagement of the European Union on these issues is not new: we have a common program since 1972.
In 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest carbon market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reducing its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (based on 1990 levels).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing today's world.
The increasingly high temperatures could lead to the total disappearance of the Arctic ice cap by 2050.
The bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is omnipresent in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases increases as air pollution worsens.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's look at these people, growing in number day by day, ready to act to challenge their ways of life. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
The sentence translated from French to English is:  "Companies are also getting involved, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy."
But it is the policymakers and politicians, at the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let us make a green Europe our first political priority for the years to come, centered on three fronts.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit planetary warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the net emissions of carbon dioxide from the EU must be brought to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we also need to apply strict limits on CO2 emissions for new private cars, public transportation, as well as commercial maritime and air transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent of electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a genuine circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Each year, 8 billion tons of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work today by launching, for example, an European initiative to combat the planned obsolescence of household and electronic devices, and in eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, the populations of wild species have declined by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations Conference on Biodiversity, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen the EU legislation for species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We also need to launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) about revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to accompany this green transition.
But these colossal works that lie ahead of us, we will not be able to accomplish them if they are still being borne by the same people – and the most vulnerable among them – who are asked to shoulder their costs.
All measures envisaged must therefore be primarily designed to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must start working with our partners today for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Here's the translation of the given French sentence into English:  "For it is pointless to have strict European regulations on pesticides or forest management if our imported foods and wood are produced without respecting sustainability criteria."
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the new political cycle of the EU.
Because we are in a situation of acute ecological debt, and it would be highly justified for the Stability and Growth Pact, which applies to the public finances of member states, to find an equivalent for green objectives of a Green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not fear to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of eco-design legislation and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in annual investments to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
It is a achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, by making the most of private sector investments, could still strengthen the Union's ability to act.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway’s sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a longer-term perspective and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney termed the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, but also on the subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, about integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these construction sites and projects, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to succeed, we must set ambitious goals and both short-term and long-term "missions" that have genuine social resonance.
With the Member States and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to avoid the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal." But it is not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
